  "prompt": "I have my exams coming up. Personal issues are bothering me a lot. I don't want to mess up my studies this time. I'm not able to concentrate. I'm stressed emotionally and mentally. What should I do?",
  "response": "I'm really sorry to hear you're going through such a tough time. Balancing personal issues and studies can be overwhelming, but there are steps you can take to manage your stress and focus better on your exams. Here\u2019s a practical plan to help you:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Acknowledge Your Feelings**\n- It\u2019s okay to feel stressed or distracted. Accept that you\u2019re dealing with a lot, and it\u2019s normal to feel this way.  \n- Journaling about your emotions can help you process them and clear your mind.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Break Down Your Tasks**\n- Divide your study material into smaller, manageable chunks. Focus on one topic or section at a time.  \n- Use a timer (like the Pomodoro Technique: 25 minutes of study, 5 minutes of break) to stay focused without feeling overwhelmed.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Prioritize Self-Care**\n- **Sleep:** Ensure you\u2019re getting 7\u20138 hours of sleep. Lack of sleep can worsen stress and reduce focus.  \n- **Eat well:** Fuel your body with nutritious food to keep your energy levels stable.  \n- **Exercise:** Even a short walk or light stretching can reduce stress and improve concentration.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Create a Study Routine**\n- Set a fixed schedule for studying and stick to it. Include regular breaks to avoid burnout.  \n- Study during your peak focus times (e.g., morning or evening) when you feel most alert.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Limit Distractions**\n- Turn off notifications on your phone or use apps like Forest or Focus@Will to stay on track.  \n- Find a quiet, comfortable place to study where you won\u2019t be interrupted.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Seek Emotional Support**\n- Talk to someone you trust\u2014a friend, family member, or counselor. Sharing your feelings can lighten the emotional load.  \n- If personal issues are too overwhelming, consider speaking to a therapist or counselor for professional guidance.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Practice Mindfulness**\n- Try meditation, deep breathing, or mindfulness exercises to calm your mind. Even 5\u201310 minutes a day can make a difference.  \n- Apps like Headspace or Calm can guide you through relaxation techniques.\n\n---\n\n### **8. Reframe Your Thoughts**\n- Instead of thinking, \u201cI\u2019m going to mess up,\u201d remind yourself, \u201cI\u2019m doing my best, and that\u2019s enough.\u201d  \n- Focus on progress, not perfection. Small steps are still steps forward.\n\n---\n\n### **9. Stay Positive**\n- Visualize yourself succeeding in your exams. Positive thinking can boost your confidence and motivation.  \n- Reward yourself after completing study sessions (e.g., a treat, a favorite show, or some relaxation time).\n\n---\n\n### **10. Seek Academic Help if Needed**\n- If you\u2019re struggling with certain subjects, reach out to teachers, classmates, or online resources for clarification.  \n- Don\u2019t hesitate to ask for help\u2014it\u2019s a sign of strength, not weakness.\n\n---\n\n### **11. Take One Day at a Time**\n- Focus on what you can do today, rather than worrying about everything at once.  \n- Celebrate small wins, like finishing a chapter or understanding a difficult concept.\n\n---\n\nRemember, you\u2019re not alone in this. It\u2019s okay to feel stressed, but with the right strategies, you can manage your emotions and perform well in your exams. Be kind to yourself\u2014you\u2019re doing the best you can. Good luck, and take it step by step! \ud83c\udf40",
  "temperature": 1.0,
